I have the 2019 Xperia 1, and I tend to play a lot of emulators on this device since the Snapdragon 855 is still very solid for emulation and more in 2021.  I didn't want to deal with Bluetooth due to input lag, so I was hoping for a true controller that can plus into USB C and I can have everything on my hands.  I saw a video of the earlier generation X2 from Retro Game Corps's YouTube page, and the X2 caught my attention.  GameSir stated that Xperia 1 phones will work on their device, and thus I did an order.Glad I did, it is excellent for my needs.  I was worried that the placement of the D-Pad being below the left analog stick will be an issue, but it wasn't a problem at all.  It is a good D-Pad that is great for 2D games.  Is it the best?  No, but most people won't have an issue with it.  The buttons are solid and so are the analog sticks.  Most people who will run it for emulation will not have an problem with the unit.  Since the button layout is the Nintendo layout (not XBox layout which is common on Android apps), you will have to adjust the button layout on a program/game.  Not all games support changing buttons, so you might have issues with the button layout using this.  If you are into racing games, the R2/L2 buttons are digital buttons and not analog.Due to how wide the Xperia 1 phones are, you will have to stretch out the X2 to its limit in order to put the Xperia in the X2.  The USB C connector on the X2 is great since it moves up and down, which will help reduce stress on the USB C connector on your phones.  While the X2 will work with most phone cases, I would be careful and not use the X2 with the Xperia 1 phones with thick cases.  I currently have the Spigen Rugged Armor Case for the Xperia 1 and it is not a thick case at all.  I was able to put the Xperia 1 in the X2 with this case on, but any thicker phone case it wouldn't fit.  But if the phone was smaller then the Xperia 1 with a phone case that is thicker then it should fit just fine on the X2.There is also an USB-C connector at the bottom left corner of the X2, since it is a pass-thru USB-C Connector.  You can use it for charging or anything you want to use it for USB-C wise.  Almost forgot, since the USB C connector on the X2 will be on the left side, some apps may not work since they are used to be in horizontal mode when the USB C connector is on its right side.X2 is pricey, but I gotta admit with the Xperia 1 in the X2 it feels great, my hands don't hurt when using it, and just feels solid.  If you do a lot of emulation of gaming with a D-Pad that supports different controllers, then I highly recommend the X2 new edition with the D-Pad.  Also gets a plus for me since it supports the Xperia 1 phones and its weird aspect ratio.

Read more'}, {'Reviewer Name': 'T M', 'Rating': '4.0 out of 5 stars', 'Title': 'HUGE', 'Date': 'Reviewed in Egypt on 28 February 2024', 'Review Body': "It's a great phone but absolutely humongous and a pain to carry or use with one hand, and I have big hands. I am coming from an S10 which has served me incredibly well for the past 5 years but I wanted a bigger screen because my sight isn't what it used to be. I was between the Ultra and the plus and decided to go with the ultra for the snapdragon and the anti glare display, but now I regret not going with the regular 24 and saving 20K in the process. The gain in screen size, even compared to the standard S10, isn't that big of a deal and cannot justify the overall size and bulk.  I also hate the fact that they changed the UI navigation gestures, the new gestures are hit and miss but that applies to all S24 models.It was a good bundle deal from amazon though who generously threw in the original silicone case besides the galaxy buds fe and the free 2 year screen insurance samsung egypt offers early buyers. The free screen insurance is a little tricky to activate though. You need to log into your samsung members app, discover, tap the benefits tab and select the screen insurance, then manually register for it. The item listed here is the phone ONLY, if you are trying to buy the BUNDLE like I did, it's a different listing and will be clearly titled bundle. Phone and accessories were delivered together the same day. Delivery required a PIN as with all high value items. All items were sealed as expected from amazon, and the phone's warranty card was wedged in the box as usual. This is only for your own assurance, since from experience, you don't need the card for warranty claims as Samsung Egypt can look up the local warranty information if any with the phone's serial number.If you know exactly what you are getting and have used a recent ultra or note phone, go right ahead, you will not be disappointed aside from the new navigation gestures if you use them instead of the buttons like me; but if you are on the fence and trying to decide which S24 model to buy, I suggest you see them in person first. I know I would choose differently if I did. I have the 2019 Xperia 1, and I tend to play a lot of emulators on this device since the Snapdragon 855 is still very solid for emulation and more in 2021.  I didn't want to deal with Bluetooth due to input lag, so I was hoping for a true controller that can plus into USB C and I can have everything on my hands.  I saw a video of the earlier generation X2 from Retro Game Corps's YouTube page, and the X2 caught my attention.  GameSir stated that Xperia 1 phones will work on their device, and thus I did an order.Glad I did, it is excellent for my needs.  I was worried that the placement of the D-Pad being below the left analog stick will be an issue, but it wasn't a problem at all.  It is a good D-Pad that is great for 2D games.  Is it the best?  No, but most people won't have an issue with it.  The buttons are solid and so are the analog sticks.  Most people who will run it for emulation will not have an problem with the unit.  Since the button layout is the Nintendo layout (not XBox layout which is common on Android apps), you will have to adjust the button layout on a program/game.  Not all games support changing buttons, so you might have issues with the button layout using this.  If you are into racing games, the R2/L2 buttons are digital buttons and not analog.Due to how wide the Xperia 1 phones are, you will have to stretch out the X2 to its limit in order to put the Xperia in the X2.  The USB C connector on the X2 is great since it moves up and down, which will help reduce stress on the USB C connector on your phones.  While the X2 will work with most phone cases, I would be careful and not use the X2 with the Xperia 1 phones with thick cases.  I currently have the Spigen Rugged Armor Case for the Xperia 1 and it is not a thick case at all.  I was able to put the Xperia 1 in the X2 with this case on, but any thicker phone case it wouldn't fit.  But if the phone was smaller then the Xperia 1 with a phone case that is thicker then it should fit just fine on the X2.There is also an USB-C connector at the bottom left corner of the X2, since it is a pass-thru USB-C Connector.  You can use it for charging or anything you want to use it for USB-C wise.  Almost forgot, since the USB C connector on the X2 will be on the left side, some apps may not work since they are used to be in horizontal mode when the USB C connector is on its right side.X2 is pricey, but I gotta admit with the Xperia 1 in the X2 it feels great, my hands don't hurt when using it, and just feels solid.  If you do a lot of emulation of gaming with a D-Pad that supports different controllers, then I highly recommend the X2 new edition with the D-Pad.  Also gets a plus for me since it supports the Xperia 1 phones and its weird aspect ratio.
